# Vaultwarden

## Overview

Vaultwarden is a self-hosted password manager used to securely store homelab credentials, service logins, notes, and other sensitive information.

This deployment runs in Docker and is routed through Traefik using HTTPS.

Vaultwarden is compatible with Bitwarden clients, but it is much lighter than the official Bitwarden self-hosted stack. This makes it a good fit for a Raspberry Pi homelab environment.

## Why I Added This

As my homelab grew, I started needing a better way to keep track of passwords, admin accounts, service logins, and recovery information.

Instead of storing passwords in plain text files, notes, or spreadsheets, I wanted to use a real password manager with encrypted storage.

This project helps me practice:

- Secure self-hosting
- Docker Compose deployments
- Reverse proxy routing with Traefik
- HTTPS with a custom domain
- Managing sensitive services in a homelab
- Documenting security-related infrastructure

## Service Details

| Item | Details |
|---|---|
| Service | Vaultwarden |
| Purpose | Self-hosted password manager |
| Platform | Docker |
| Reverse Proxy | Traefik |
| Access URL | `https://vaultwarden.anthonylearchive.com` |
| Data Directory | `/opt/stacks/vaultwarden/vw-data` |
| Container Name | `vaultwarden` |

## Folder Location on Server

Vaultwarden is deployed on the Raspberry Pi under:

```bash
/opt/stacks/vaultwarden
```
The main files include:

/opt/stacks/vaultwarden/
├── docker-compose.yml
└── vw-data/

Don't delete /opt/stacks/vaultwarden/vw-data

